Greetings from the San Juan Islands, where I=E2=80=99ve been (mostly) off t=
he grid. My home here remains blissfully WiFi-free and just beyond the reac=
h of cell service, so messages from the outside world arrive only when I ve=
nture down to the nearby cove to go crabbing or take the kids to the beach.

Unsurprisingly, most of the current inbound these days pertains to David Za=
slav and the fate of Warner Bros. Discovery, which hit a sub-$7-per-share n=
adir after last week=E2=80=99s humiliating, post-NBA quarterly earnings cal=
l. To wit: over the weekend, I heard that a few veterans of the company=E2=
=80=99s TimeWarner and WarnerMedia iterations had grown so disillusioned wi=
th Zaz=E2=80=99s performance that they were fantasizing about Jeff Bewkes=
=E2=80=94the patrician former chief executive who guided TimeWarner out of =
its ill-fated AOL merger and into its $85 billion
sale to AT&T=E2=80=94returning Iger-like to shepherd the company out of its=
 current morass.

Of course, this was just wishful and wistful thinking to pass the sultry su=
mmer hours in East Hampton, and there are at least a dozen reasons why it w=
ould never happen: Zaz is still there and defiant as ever; John Malone and =
the rest of the WBD board don=E2=80=99t necessarily want a new C.E.O.; and =
Bewkes himself wouldn=E2=80=99t do it if asked. A Bewkes spokesperson told =
me: =E2=80=9CJeff is happy and content in his post-Time Warner life and has=
 no interest or intention of ever returning to the company.=E2=80=9D (Why w=
ould he?)

Still, the nostalgia is understandable. After two-plus years of aggressive =
cost-cutting and a series of management failures from Hollywood to Hudson Y=
ards, Zaz has now lost the key sports rights that sustained his television =
business and, in this month=E2=80=99s earnings call, reported a $9.1 billio=
n write-down of its cable business and a roughly $300
million earnings miss. At this point, a WBD share barely covers the cost of=
 a single oyster at LDV at The Maidstone. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s an unfixabl=
e mess,=E2=80=9D one veteran Warner executive told me this week, =E2=80=9Cw=
hich, to his credit, [Bewkes] understood years ago.=E2=80=9D

Not everyone is so bearish on Zaz and WBD, of course (though, increasingly,=
 more and more are). On Tuesday, one of his friends and fellow entertainmen=
t executives sought to temper the angst by arguing that Zaz still has the b=
est and most under-used I.P. in entertainment as well as long-maturity, low=
-cost debt. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think he needs to be too anxious,=E2=
=80=9D this exec said. And the NBA was =E2=80=9Ctoo expensive=E2=80=9D anyw=
ay.

My Puck partner Bill Cohan, currently writing from another island in anothe=
r ocean, has long had a more sanguine view of Zaz=E2=80=99s performance, as=
 well: Zaz is reducing the debt and generating free cash flow, which is his=
 mandate, after all=E2=80=94stock price and staff
morale and the sentiments of the creative community be damned. And while I =
often take a far more critical tack on Zaz, I understand Bill=E2=80=99s wel=
l-informed point of view, too. In many ways, we=E2=80=99re just analyzing d=
ifferent sides of the same coin, which ideally provides you, dear reader, w=
ith a more holistic understanding of both the motivations for Zaz=E2=80=99s=
 actions as well as their effects.

So, in today=E2=80=99s edition of In the Room, Bill presents the bull case,=
 such as it is, for Zaslav and WBD.

