Zazology

As I=E2=80=99ve heard him surmise in the past, Zaz thinks there are going t=
o be five surviving global content providers at the end of the day: Amazon =
Prime, YouTube, Netflix, Disney, and WBD. (He doesn=E2=80=99t think that a =
purely domestic player, such as NBCU, will make it.) Whether or not this pr=
ophecy bears out probably comes down to creative dealmaking on his part, pa=
rticularly now that WBD is out from under from the tax restrictions of the =
Reverse Morris Trust that governed the merger of the Discovery and WarnerMe=
dia assets.

Zaz has been busy creating various partnerships=E2=80=94with Disney (to bun=
dle D+ and Hulu with Max); with Disney and Fox (to create Venu); with Brazi=
l=E2=80=99s Globo=E2=80=94but that=E2=80=99s only one part of what Zaz hope=
s will be a winning formula. Will Zaz end up with Paramount+ and its 60 mil=
lion subscribers, if David Ellison sees fit
to hive the streaming service off? Could he end up with CBS and its local t=
elevision affiliates? It=E2=80=99s not as far-fetched as you may think, giv=
en that WBD=E2=80=99s balance sheet continues to improve quarter after quar=
ter.

Although it never went anywhere, Sony and Apollo did surface the idea of pa=
ying $26 billion for Paramount Global. That=E2=80=99s an interesting benchm=
ark from savvy buyers. According to my calculations, WBD=E2=80=99s studio i=
s three times bigger than Paramount=E2=80=99s. Its television business is f=
our or five times bigger. Its content library is two to three times bigger.=
 If Paramount Global is worth $26 billion, then WBD has got to be worth $75=
 billion, according to that math. (Again, this is not investment advice.) L=
ess the $38 billion in debt, this back-of-the-envelope arithmetic suggests =
the WBD equity is worth around $37 billion, or at least twice what it=E2=80=
=99s trading for these days. (Please, not investment advice=E2=80=A6)

I have no idea if Zaz will get to the
promised land. He=E2=80=99s on the high wire at the moment. I suspect he=E2=
=80=99s still got the support of John Malone, the WBD director and major st=
akeholder who is also Zaz=E2=80=99s mentor. Malone is probably advising him=
 to ignore the noise, stay focused on paying down debt, keep creating great=
 content, and maneuver into a position to save some of the other swimmers w=
ho are drowning. But there are other big shareholders, too, such as Vanguar=
d, which owns 10 percent of WBD, and the Newhouse family, which owns 8 perc=
ent, and BlackRock, which owns 6.3 percent, and State Street, which owns 5.=
6 percent. Will Zaz be able to keep these other wolves at bay? Will an acti=
vist investor hop into the WBD fray to try to implement a version of the br=
eak-up plan that BofA Securities analyst Jessica Reif Ehrlich proposed last=
 month, and which briefly got the stock moving up? Is Zaz on a short leash =
or a long rope?

I don=E2=80=99t know the answer to any of these questions. But I
still believe the market is overreacting to the wave of bad news at WBD. An=
d if and when the per-sub carriage fees are renegotiated for more than the =
market expects, or if and when the third-quarter streaming subs come in hig=
her than anticipated, or even if and when Beetlejuice and Joker: Folie =C3=
=A0 Deux overperform, the narrative could turn.

Remember, it wasn=E2=80=99t that long ago that Netflix looked to be down in=
 the dumps, too. The company reported subscriptions fell by 200,000 or so i=
n the first quarter of 2022, and the supposedly savvy investor Bill Ackman =
dumped ( https://www.theinformation.com/articles/what-netflixs-stock-recove=
ry-and-ackmans-mistake-tells-us?utm_campaign=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
88%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F19%2F24%29&u=
tm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42ab=
d12a ) his $1.1 billion investment in the company
that April, perfecting a $400 million loss. Bad move. That was the moment A=
ckman should have been buying more Netflix, not selling. The stock has pret=
ty much tripled since then. So just when everyone seems to think it=E2=80=
=99s over for you can be the very moment things begin to turn around. I=E2=
=80=99m not saying that=E2=80=99s necessarily where WBD is currently, but i=
t=E2=80=99s always darkest before the dawn.

