           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 0;">Greetings from the San Juan=
 Islands, where I=E2=80=99ve been (mostly) off the grid. My home here remai=
ns blissfully WiFi-free and just beyond the reach of cell service, so messa=
ges from the outside world arrive only when I venture down to the nearby co=
ve to go crabbing or take the kids to the beach.<br/><br/>Unsurprisingly, m=
ost of the current inbound these days pertains to <b>David Zaslav</b> and t=
he fate of Warner Bros. Discovery, which hit a sub-$7-per-share nadir after=
 last week=E2=80=99s humiliating, post-NBA quarterly earnings call. To wit:=
 over the weekend, I heard that a few veterans of the company=E2=80=99s Tim=
eWarner and WarnerMedia iterations had grown so disillusioned with Zaz=E2=
=80=99s performance that they were fantasizing about <b>Jeff Bewkes</b>=E2=
=80=94the patrician former chief executive who guided TimeWarner out of its=
 ill-fated AOL merger and into its $85 billion
sale to AT&amp;T=E2=80=94returning <b>Iger</b>-like to shepherd the company=
 out of its current morass.<br/><br/>Of course, this was just wishful and w=
istful thinking to pass the sultry summer hours in East Hampton, and there =
are at least a dozen reasons why it would never happen: Zaz is still there =
and defiant as ever; <b>John Malone </b>and the rest of the WBD board don=
=E2=80=99t necessarily <i>want</i> a new C.E.O.; and Bewkes himself wouldn=
=E2=80=99t do it if asked. A Bewkes spokesperson told me: =E2=80=9CJeff is =
happy and content in his post-Time Warner life and has no interest or inten=
tion of ever returning to the company.=E2=80=9D (Why would he?)<br/><br/>St=
ill, the nostalgia is understandable. After two-plus years of aggressive co=
st-cutting and a series of management failures from Hollywood to Hudson Yar=
ds, Zaz has now lost the key sports rights that sustained his television bu=
siness and, in this month=E2=80=99s earnings call, reported a $9.1 billion =
write-down of its cable business and a roughly $300
million earnings miss. At this point, a WBD share barely covers the cost of=
 a single oyster at LDV at The Maidstone. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s an unfixabl=
e mess,=E2=80=9D one veteran Warner executive told me this week, =E2=80=9Cw=
hich, to his credit, [Bewkes] understood years ago.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Not <=
i>everyone</i> is so bearish on Zaz and WBD, of course (though, increasingl=
y, more and more are). On Tuesday, one of his friends and fellow entertainm=
ent executives sought to temper the angst by arguing that Zaz still has the=
 best and most under-used I.P. in entertainment as well as long-maturity, l=
ow-cost debt. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think he needs to be too anxious,=E2=
=80=9D this exec said. And the NBA was =E2=80=9Ctoo expensive=E2=80=9D anyw=
ay.<br/><br/>My Puck partner <b>Bill Cohan</b>, currently writing from anot=
her island in another ocean, has long had a more sanguine view of Zaz=E2=80=
=99s performance, as well: Zaz <i>is </i>reducing the debt and generating f=
ree cash flow, which <i>is</i> his mandate, after all=E2=80=94stock price a=
nd staff
morale and the sentiments of the creative community be damned. And while I =
often take a far more critical tack on Zaz, I understand Bill=E2=80=99s <i>=
well</i>-informed point of view, too. In many ways, we=E2=80=99re just anal=
yzing different sides of the same coin, which ideally provides you, dear re=
ader, with a more holistic understanding of both the motivations for Zaz=E2=
=80=99s actions as well as their effects. <br/><br/>So, in today=E2=80=99s =
edition of In the Room, Bill presents the bull case, such as it is, for Zas=
lav and WBD. <br/><br/><i>P.S.: You asked, and we=E2=80=99ve delivered=E2=
=80=A6 another member survey, which will help us continue to improve your P=
uck experience. It should only take a minute or two. <u><a href=3D"https://=
