obably comes down to creative dealmaking on his part, particularly now that=
 WBD is out from under from the tax restrictions of the Reverse Morris Trus=
t that governed the merger of the Discovery and WarnerMedia assets. <br/><b=
r/>Zaz has been busy creating various partnerships=E2=80=94with Disney (to =
bundle D+ and Hulu with Max); with Disney and Fox (to create Venu); with Br=
azil=E2=80=99s Globo=E2=80=94but that=E2=80=99s only one part of what Zaz h=
opes will be a winning formula. Will Zaz end up with Paramount+ and its 60 =
million subscribers, if <b>David Ellison </b>sees fit
to hive the streaming service off? Could he end up with CBS and its local t=
elevision affiliates? It=E2=80=99s not as far-fetched as you may think, giv=
en that WBD=E2=80=99s balance sheet continues to improve quarter after quar=
ter. <br/><br/>Although it never went anywhere, Sony and Apollo did surface=
 the idea of paying $26 billion for Paramount Global. That=E2=80=99s an int=
eresting benchmark from savvy buyers. According to my calculations, WBD=E2=
=80=99s studio is three times bigger than Paramount=E2=80=99s. Its televisi=
on business is four or five times bigger. Its content library is two to thr=
ee times bigger. If Paramount Global is worth $26 billion, then WBD has got=
 to be worth $75 billion, according to that math. (Again, this is not inves=
tment advice.) Less the $38 billion in debt, this back-of-the-envelope arit=
hmetic suggests the WBD equity is worth around $37 billion, or at least twi=
ce what it=E2=80=99s trading for these days. (Please, not investment advice=
=E2=80=A6)<br/><br/>I have no idea if Zaz will get to the
promised land. He=E2=80=99s on the high wire at the moment. I suspect he=E2=
=80=99s still got the support of <b>John Malone</b>, the WBD director and m=
ajor stakeholder who is also Zaz=E2=80=99s mentor. Malone is probably advis=
ing him to ignore the noise, stay focused on paying down debt, keep creatin=
g great content, and maneuver into a position to save some of the other swi=
mmers who are drowning. But there are other big shareholders, too, such as =
Vanguard, which owns 10 percent of WBD, and the <b>Newhouse</b> family, whi=
ch owns 8 percent, and BlackRock, which owns 6.3 percent, and State Street,=
 which owns 5.6 percent. Will Zaz be able to keep these other wolves at bay=
? Will an activist investor hop into the WBD fray to try to implement a ver=
sion of the break-up plan that BofA Securities analyst <b>Jessica Reif Ehrl=
ich</b> proposed last month, and which briefly got the stock moving up? Is =
Zaz on a short leash or a long rope? <br/><br/>I don=E2=80=99t know the ans=
wer to any of these questions. But I
still believe the market is overreacting to the wave of bad news at WBD. An=
d if and when the per-sub carriage fees are renegotiated for more than the =
market expects, or if and when the third-quarter streaming subs come in hig=
her than anticipated, or even if and when <i>Beetlejuice</i> and <i>Joker: =
Folie =C3=A0 Deux </i>overperform, the narrative could turn. <br/><br/>Reme=
mber, it wasn=E2=80=99t that long ago that Netflix looked to be down in the=
 dumps, too. The company reported subscriptions fell by 200,000 or so in th=
e first quarter of 2022, and the supposedly savvy investor <b>Bill Ackman <=
